article.headline: Polk records seventh straight double-double
article.linkText: Polk sparks No. 24 Arizona in win over No. 25 Lobos
article.story:
TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Shawntinice Polk doesn't get caught up in
numbers. Maybe that's because they just seem to gather around her
name in the box score.

	   The 6-foot-5 freshman had 26 points and 11 rebounds -- her
seventh straight double-double -- to lead No. (24 ESPN/USA Today, No. 23 AP) Arizona to a 70-61
victory over (No. 25 ESPN/USA Today) New Mexico on Wednesday night.

	   "It's a win, and that is all I care about -- a win,'' Polk said.

	   "We tried to defend her with two players,'' New Mexico coach
Don Flanagan said. "She is just a physical presence with excellent
hands.''

	   Aimee Grzyb had 13 points and Krista Warren added 12 for the
Wildcats (5-2), who snapped New Mexico's eight-game winning streak.

	   Jordan Adams scored 17 points for the Lobos, and Mandi Moore had
16, seven rebounds and seven assists. New Mexico (8-2) hadn't lost
since its opener at Southern California.

	   Polk was a key figure down the stretch for Arizona.

	   After Arizona's Natalie Jones was hit in the face on a screen
and had to leave the game with 11:32 remaining, the Wildcats scored
six straight points to take a 50-44 lead. The final basket was a
short jumper by Polk.

	   "I didn't expect her to be this good,'' said Adams, the Lobos'
6-3 center. "She passes more than we thought. She was taller than
we expected. She surprised me a lot.''

	   Adams answered with a basket, but Polk made a layup before and
after a 3-pointer by Grzyb for a 55-46 lead with 7:54 to play.

	   Grzyb made another 3-pointer with 3:33 left, giving the Wildcats
to a 64-54 lead.

	   Grzyb was hurt during the game when New Mexico beat the Wildcats
75-67 last season, and the bad blood between the teams was evident
in the physical nature of the game.

	   Arizona coach Joan Bonvicini said Jones' injury helped motivate
her club.

	   "We take that personally,'' Bonvicini said. "That is about
protecting your teammates.''
